McDormand: OUR
RELATIONSHIP TO THE POTATO

01:25:40.930 --> 01:25:44.260
BEGAN IN THE ANDES
MOUNTAINS OF SOUTH AMERICA.

01:25:44.260 --> 01:25:47.300
IN PLACES LIKE PISAC IN PERU,

01:25:47.300 --> 01:25:49.130
PEOPLE HAVE LONG DEPENDED

01:25:49.130 --> 01:25:53.460
ON THE POTATO FOR SURVIVAL.

01:25:53.460 --> 01:25:55.900
TO MAKE SURE THEY
GROW ENOUGH POTATOES,

01:25:55.900 --> 01:25:59.100
THEY'VE DEVELOPED AN
ASTONISHING DEGREE

01:25:59.100 --> 01:26:01.230
OF AGRICULTURAL CREATIVITY.

01:26:01.230 --> 01:26:05.130
Man: WE RECKON THAT THERE ARE

01:26:05.130 --> 01:26:10.900
MORE THAN 5,000
DIFFERENT POTATO VARIETIES
IN THE ANDEAN REGION.

01:26:10.900 --> 01:26:14.430
THERE ARE TREMENDOUS
COMBINATIONS

01:26:14.430 --> 01:26:17.360
OF COLORS, AS WELL AS SHAPES.

01:26:17.360 --> 01:26:21.500
YOU FIND VERY
ELONGATED POTATO TUBERS

01:26:21.500 --> 01:26:23.860
THAT DON'T LOOK
POTATOES AT ALL,

01:26:23.860 --> 01:26:25.930
TO VERY, VERY STRANGE,

01:26:25.930 --> 01:26:29.800
WITH VERY DIFFERENT
PROTUBERANCES,

01:26:29.800 --> 01:26:31.960
THAT LOOK VERY,
VERY STRANGE TO YOU.

01:26:31.960 --> 01:26:34.800
McDormand: IT WAS IN
THE ANDES THAT PEOPLE

01:26:34.800 --> 01:26:39.600
FIRST DOMESTICATED THE POTATO
PLANT AROUND 8,000 YEARS AGO.

01:26:39.600 --> 01:26:43.230
TO DO THAT, THEY HAD TO
OVERCOME A BIG OBSTACLE.

01:26:43.230 --> 01:26:46.360
Pollan: THE POTATO IN
THE WILD IS POISONOUS.

01:26:46.360 --> 01:26:50.200
YOU KNOW, IT'S ONE OF THOSE
CROPS THAT PRODUCES SOLANINE,

01:26:50.200 --> 01:26:51.800
WHICH IS AN ALKALOID
WHICH IS POISONOUS.

01:26:51.800 --> 01:26:54.400
AND, IN FACT, POTATOES STILL
PRODUCE IT, BY THE WAY.

01:26:54.400 --> 01:26:57.030
IF YOU ALLOW YOUR POTATO
TO GET EXPOSED TO LIGHT

01:26:57.030 --> 01:26:59.830
AND IT TURNS GREEN, IT'S
PRODUCING SOLANINE,

01:26:59.830 --> 01:27:00.900
AND YOU SHOULDN'T EAT IT.

01:27:00.900 --> 01:27:03.060
McDormand: BUT IN
THE PLANT WORLD,

01:27:03.060 --> 01:27:05.560
THERE ARE ALWAYS
EXCEPTIONS TO THE RULE.

01:27:05.560 --> 01:27:10.300
GENES INEVITABLY MUTATE,
AND PLANTS CHANGE.

01:27:10.300 --> 01:27:13.030
Pollan: PEOPLE DID A
LOT OF TRIAL AND ERROR,

01:27:13.030 --> 01:27:17.330
TASTING POTATOES AND
SPITTING THEM OUT,

01:27:17.330 --> 01:27:19.230
AND THEN, EVENTUALLY,
YOU FIND ONE --

01:27:19.230 --> 01:27:22.760
LIKE, HEY, THIS ONE
DOESN'T HAVE THAT TASTE.

01:27:22.760 --> 01:27:26.530
AND THOSE WOULD BE THE
POTATOES THAT WE WOULD SAVE.

01:27:26.530 --> 01:27:29.760
McDormand: OVER TIME,
THE PERUVIANS ACHIEVED

01:27:29.760 --> 01:27:31.760
GREAT SUCCESS AS
POTATO FARMERS,

01:27:31.760 --> 01:27:34.460
NOT BY TRYING TO
CONTROL NATURE,

01:27:34.460 --> 01:27:35.760
BUT BY ADAPTING TO IT.

01:27:35.760 --> 01:27:38.560
Pollan: WHENEVER YOU'RE
MOVING UP IN ALTITUDE,

01:27:38.560 --> 01:27:41.500
YOU'RE HAVING A RADICAL
CHANGE IN CLIMATE.

01:27:41.500 --> 01:27:43.300
AND ONE SIDE OF A HILL WILL HAVE

01:27:43.300 --> 01:27:47.330
A VERY DIFFERENT
CLIMATE THAN ANOTHER.

01:27:47.330 --> 01:27:50.030
THE WAY THE EARLY
PERUVIANS DEALT WITH THAT

01:27:50.030 --> 01:27:53.130
WAS TO GROW MANY DIFFERENT
VARIETIES OF POTATOES

01:27:53.130 --> 01:27:58.200
AND PRESERVE THE DIVERSITY,
SO THAT ON A PLOT

01:27:58.200 --> 01:28:00.660
OF THIS KIND OF
FACING TOWARD THE SUN

01:28:00.660 --> 01:28:03.330
AT THIS KIND OF ALTITUDE,
YOU PLANT THIS ONE.

01:28:03.330 --> 01:28:06.200
AND ON THIS PLANT -- JUST ON
THE OTHER SIDE OF THE HILL,

01:28:06.200 --> 01:28:08.060
YOU PLANT THIS POTATO.

01:28:08.060 --> 01:28:11.730
AND THIS WAS A WAY OF GAINING
CONTROL OVER THEIR FATE.

01:28:11.730 --> 01:28:13.600
BECAUSE IF SOMETHING HAPPENED

01:28:13.600 --> 01:28:15.860
ON THAT ONE PLOT
AT THAT ALTITUDE,

01:28:15.860 --> 01:28:18.500
THEY WOULD STILL
HAVE OTHER POTATOES.

01:28:18.500 --> 01:28:24.400
Roca: THE ANDEAN REGION HAS
MANY NICHES FOR GROWING CROPS.

01:28:24.400 --> 01:28:27.760
AND THE POTATO WAS ABLE TO
ADAPT TO DIFFERENT AREAS.

01:28:27.760 --> 01:28:29.960
THAT'S WHY THERE WERE
SO MANY VARIETIES

01:28:29.960 --> 01:28:33.400
DEVELOPED FOR DIFFERENT
USES AND DIFFERENT PURPOSES

01:28:33.400 --> 01:28:34.400
ALONG THE ANDES.

01:28:34.400 --> 01:28:37.860
McDormand: FAUSTINO PACCO IS 24.

01:28:37.860 --> 01:28:42.060
HIS FAMILY HAS BEEN GROWING
POTATOES HERE IN THE ANDES

01:28:42.060 --> 01:28:43.700
FOR HUNDREDS OF YEARS.

01:28:43.700 --> 01:28:52.400
[ SPEAKING SPANISH ]

01:28:52.400 --> 01:29:00.630
[ FLUTE PLAYING ]

01:29:00.630 --> 01:29:18.900
[ SPEAKING NATIVE LANGUAGE ]

01:29:18.900 --> 01:29:44.930
[ PACCO SPEAKING SPANISH ]

01:29:44.930 --> 01:29:50.030
McDormand: THESE ANDEAN
FARMERS ARE THE DESCENDANTS

01:29:50.030 --> 01:29:52.960
OF ONE OF THE GREAT
CIVILIZATIONS OF HISTORY --

01:29:52.960 --> 01:29:56.000
THE INCAS.

01:29:56.000 --> 01:29:59.230
THEY PRESIDED OVER ONE
OF THE MOST SOPHISTICATED

01:29:59.230 --> 01:30:00.800
AGRICULTURAL SYSTEMS ON EARTH,

01:30:00.800 --> 01:30:04.260
BASED IN LARGE
PART ON THE POTATO.

01:30:04.260 --> 01:30:08.760
BUT WHEN THE SPANISH
INVADED IN THE 16th CENTURY,

01:30:08.760 --> 01:30:11.460
THEY DESTROYED THE INCA EMPIRE

01:30:11.460 --> 01:30:14.730
AND SET THE POTATO -- AND
OUR RELATIONSHIP WITH IT --

01:30:14.730 --> 01:30:18.260
ON A NEW PHASE OF ITS JOURNEY.

01:30:18.260 --> 01:30:19.830
WHEN THE POTATO GOT TO EUROPE,

01:30:19.830 --> 01:30:23.230
IT CHANGED THE COURSE
OF EUROPEAN HISTORY.

01:30:23.230 --> 01:30:25.660
[ THUNDERCLAPS ]

01:30:25.660 --> 01:30:27.100
Pollan: BEFORE THE POTATO,

01:30:27.100 --> 01:30:30.960
THE NORTHERN TIER OF EUROPE
-- THE POPULATION WAS

01:30:30.960 --> 01:30:35.430
RELATIVELY SMALL AND WAS
HELD BACK BY REGULAR FAMINES

01:30:35.430 --> 01:30:37.660
CAUSED BY FAILURES
OF THE GRAIN HARVEST.

01:30:37.660 --> 01:30:41.560
THE FURTHER NORTH YOU GO, THE
DICIER IT IS TO GROW WHEAT.

01:30:41.560 --> 01:30:45.830
AND SO THE CENTER OF GRAVITY
IN EUROPE BEFORE THE POTATO

01:30:45.830 --> 01:30:50.860
WAS THE MEDITERRANEAN,
WHERE YOU COULD GROW
GRAIN MORE RELIABLY.

01:30:50.860 --> 01:30:56.300
THE POTATO DID VERY WELL AT
THE MORE NORTHERLY AREAS.

01:30:56.300 --> 01:30:59.730
IT DID VERY WELL
IN WETTER AREAS.

01:30:59.730 --> 01:31:05.400
AND IT DID VERY WELL
IN REALLY POOR SOILS.

01:31:05.400 --> 01:31:09.060
THIS VAST NEW SOURCE OF
CALORIES THAT COULD UNDERWRITE

01:31:09.060 --> 01:31:10.160
THE GROWTH OF THE POPULATION,

01:31:10.160 --> 01:31:15.360
SUCH AS NEVER WOULD HAVE
HAPPENED WITHOUT THE POTATO.

01:31:15.360 --> 01:31:19.400
SINCE ONE INDIVIDUAL
CAN GROW SO MUCH FOOD,

01:31:19.400 --> 01:31:22.300
YOU NEED FEWER
PEOPLE IN THE FIELDS

01:31:22.300 --> 01:31:24.560
TO SUPPORT AN URBAN POPULATION.

01:31:24.560 --> 01:31:27.730
SO IT'S REALLY HARD TO IMAGINE

01:31:27.730 --> 01:31:30.730
THE INDUSTRIAL REVOLUTION
PROCEEDING AS IT WOULD

01:31:30.730 --> 01:31:34.000
WITHOUT THE POTATO TO
KIND OF SUPPORT IT.

01:31:34.000 --> 01:31:38.500
THIS NEW WORLD FOOD
REMADE THE OLD WORLD.

01:31:38.500 --> 01:31:43.160
McDormand: THE POTATO
THRIVED IN THE SOILS
OF NORTHERN EUROPE,

01:31:43.160 --> 01:31:45.230
MOST DRAMATICALLY IN IRELAND,

01:31:45.230 --> 01:31:48.860
A COUNTRY SORELY IN
NEED OF A HEARTY FOOD.

01:31:48.860 --> 01:31:50.260
Pollan: FOR THE IRISH,

01:31:50.260 --> 01:31:52.560
THE POTATO INITIALLY
WAS A GODSEND.

01:31:52.560 --> 01:31:57.600
McDormand: IRELAND'S POOR
FARMLAND AND BAD WEATHER

01:31:57.600 --> 01:32:00.600
MADE IT A TOUGH
PLACE TO GROW CROPS.

01:32:00.600 --> 01:32:03.830
BUT THE POTATO PLANT
ACTUALLY PROSPERED

01:32:03.830 --> 01:32:05.100
IN THIS SOGGY ENVIRONMENT

01:32:05.100 --> 01:32:08.630
AND SEEMED TO END THE COUNTRY'S
LONG STRUGGLE WITH HUNGER.

01:32:08.630 --> 01:32:12.260
Pollan: IF YOU HAD
POTATOES AND COW'S MILK,

01:32:12.260 --> 01:32:13.860
YOU HAD A COMPLETE DIET.

01:32:13.860 --> 01:32:15.230
YOU HAD CALORIES, OBVIOUSLY,

01:32:15.230 --> 01:32:18.130
AND YOU HAD THE FULL
COMPLEMENT OF VITAMINS.

01:32:18.130 --> 01:32:22.230
SO THEY BECAME VERY
DEPENDENT ON THE POTATO.

01:32:22.230 --> 01:32:25.960
AND IN FACT, THE
POPULATION GREW.

01:32:25.960 --> 01:32:28.930
THE PROBLEM WAS,
HOWEVER, THAT THE IRISH

01:32:28.930 --> 01:32:31.030
WERE PLANTING ALMOST EXCLUSIVELY

01:32:31.030 --> 01:32:34.600
ONE KIND OF POTATO --
THE POTATO THEY CALLED
THE LUMPER.

01:32:34.600 --> 01:32:38.360
AND THEY PLANTED THE
LUMPER ALL OVER IRELAND.

01:32:38.360 --> 01:32:41.760
SO THE IRISH HAD
REALLY MADE THEMSELVES

01:32:41.760 --> 01:32:44.930
DEPENDENT ON THIS
ONE STRAIN OF POTATO.

01:32:44.930 --> 01:32:50.030
AND IN 1845, SOME SHIP
FROM SOUTH AMERICA

01:32:50.030 --> 01:32:52.360
WAS CARRYING A FUNGUS,

01:32:52.360 --> 01:32:57.300
AND IT WAS A
WIND-SPREAD SPORE,

01:32:57.300 --> 01:32:58.760
AND OVER THE COURSE

01:32:58.760 --> 01:33:00.930
OF A VERY FEW WEEKS,

01:33:00.930 --> 01:33:05.530
THE SPORES SPREAD
ACROSS ALL OF IRELAND,

01:33:05.530 --> 01:33:08.930
AND WITHIN DAYS OF INFECTION,
THE FIELDS WENT BLACK

01:33:08.930 --> 01:33:11.730
AND THE POTATOES IN THE
GROUND TURNED TO MUSH.

01:33:11.730 --> 01:33:17.360
McDormand: THE IRISH POTATO
FAMINE LASTED FOR THREE YEARS.

01:33:17.360 --> 01:33:22.460
IN THE END, THE FAMINE
KILLED ONE MILLION PEOPLE --

01:33:22.460 --> 01:33:26.600
ONE OUT OF EVERY EIGHT
PEOPLE IN IRELAND.

01:33:26.600 --> 01:33:32.300
Pollan: SO THE IRISH
FAMINE IS, IN A WAY,

01:33:32.300 --> 01:33:33.460
THE GREAT CAUTIONARY TALE

01:33:33.460 --> 01:33:35.460
OF PUTTING ALL YOUR
EGGS IN ONE BASKET,

01:33:35.460 --> 01:33:42.230
AND THE GREAT CAUTIONARY TALE
ABOUT MONOCULTURES OF ALL KINDS.

01:33:42.230 --> 01:33:46.230
IT'S A PARABLE ABOUT THE
IMPORTANCE OF BIODIVERSITY

01:33:46.230 --> 01:33:48.130
AND THE DANGERS OF MONOCULTURE.

01:33:48.130 --> 01:33:50.600
AND IT'S A PARABLE WE
FORGET AT OUR PERIL,

01:33:50.600 --> 01:33:54.100
BUT, IN FACT, WE'RE IN THE
PROCESS OF FORGETTING TODAY.

01:33:54.100 --> 01:33:57.660
McDormand: AND WHAT'S
MAKING US FORGET

01:33:57.660 --> 01:34:00.160
IS ONE OF OUR FAVORITE FOODS.

01:34:00.160 --> 01:34:02.830
EACH YEAR, AMERICANS CONSUME

01:34:02.830 --> 01:34:07.260
ABOUT 7.5 BILLION
POUNDS OF FRENCH FRIES.

01:34:07.260 --> 01:34:11.030
THEY ARE THE MOST POPULAR
FAST FOOD IN THE COUNTRY.

01:34:11.030 --> 01:34:14.660
Pollan: WE LOVE
OUR FRENCH FRIES.

01:34:14.660 --> 01:34:19.430
McDONALD'S KIND OF PIONEERED
THAT BEAUTIFUL RED BOX

01:34:19.430 --> 01:34:22.700
THAT HAVE TO BE TALL ENOUGH TO
KIND OF SPROUT OUT OF THE BOX

01:34:22.700 --> 01:34:24.730
LIKE A LITTLE BOUQUET
OF POTATO FLOWERS.

01:34:24.730 --> 01:34:28.800
McDormand: AND TO MAKE
THOSE LONG FRENCH FRIES,

01:34:28.800 --> 01:34:30.030
THE FAST FOOD INDUSTRY RELIES

01:34:30.030 --> 01:34:33.660
ALMOST EXCLUSIVELY ON
ONE VARIETY OF POTATO --

01:34:33.660 --> 01:34:36.760
THE RUSSET BURBANK.

01:34:36.760 --> 01:34:40.460
Pollan: AND THAT'S
WHAT McDONALD'S BUYS,

01:34:40.460 --> 01:34:44.360
BECAUSE McDONALD'S WANTS PEOPLE
TO HAVE THE SAME EXPERIENCE --

01:34:44.360 --> 01:34:48.300
THE SAME BEAUTIFUL, GOLDEN
McDONALD'S FRENCH FRIES,

01:34:48.300 --> 01:34:51.200
WHETHER YOU'RE IN
PRAGUE OR LONDON

01:34:51.200 --> 01:34:53.300
OR BEIJING OR NEW YORK OR IDAHO.

01:34:53.300 --> 01:34:55.930
McDormand: McDONALD'S
BUYS ITS FRENCH FRIES

01:34:55.930 --> 01:35:00.460
FROM POTATO PROCESSING COMPANIES
LIKE THE J.R. SIMPLOT COMPANY.

01:35:00.460 --> 01:35:04.900
THIS IS ONE OF ITS
PLANTS, IN NAMPA, IDAHO.

01:35:04.900 --> 01:35:11.660
THE POTATO WE PROCESS THE
MOST IS THE RUSSET BURBANK.

01:35:11.660 --> 01:35:13.860
THE RUSSET BURBANK
GIVES US PRETTY MUCH

01:35:13.860 --> 01:35:19.500
THE IDEAL QUALITY ATTRIBUTES,
IF WE'RE GOING TO CONVERT THEM

01:35:19.500 --> 01:35:21.460
INTO THE PRODUCT THAT
OUR CUSTOMER WANTS.

01:35:21.460 --> 01:35:25.060
Pollan: SO YOU SEE
HOW MONOCULTURES

01:35:25.060 --> 01:35:27.660
ON THE PLATE LEAD TO
MONOCULTURES ON THE LAND,

01:35:27.660 --> 01:35:31.800
AND THAT A DESIRE FOR SOMETHING
LIKE THAT PERFECT FRENCH FRY

01:35:31.800 --> 01:35:34.260
HAS A WHOLE, YOU KNOW,
CARRIES A WHOLE CHAIN

01:35:34.260 --> 01:35:37.130
OF CONSEQUENCES, ALL THE
WAY BACK TO THE FARM.

01:35:37.130 --> 01:35:40.600
McDormand: THIS IDAHO FARM,

01:35:40.600 --> 01:35:44.600
WHOSE FIELDS EXTEND
FOR NEARLY 100 MILES,

01:35:44.600 --> 01:35:47.300
IS RUN BY RYAN CRANNEY
AND HIS FAMILY.

01:35:47.300 --> 01:35:52.330
LIKE MOST IDAHO
POTATO FARMERS,

01:35:52.330 --> 01:35:54.030
THE CRANNEYS SELL
MOST OF THEIR CROP

01:35:54.030 --> 01:35:57.100
TO THE PROCESSING
COMPANIES THAT MAKE

01:35:57.100 --> 01:35:59.230
IF YOU WANT TO GET THEM IN
BEFORE THEY GET FROZEN,

01:35:59.230 --> 01:36:00.230
THEN WE NEED TO KEEP DIGGING.

01:36:00.230 --> 01:36:03.130
McDormand: SO, TO
SATISFY THEIR CUSTOMERS,

01:36:03.130 --> 01:36:05.760
THE CRANNEYS GROW MOSTLY

01:36:05.760 --> 01:36:07.560
Man: THAT OUGHT TO
MAKE GOOD FRENCH FRIES.

01:36:07.560 --> 01:36:11.930
Man: I THINK THERE
ARE OTHER VARIETIES

01:36:11.930 --> 01:36:13.600
THAT ARE EASIER TO GROW,

01:36:13.600 --> 01:36:16.630
BUT THAT'S WHAT THE CONSUMER
DEMANDS, IS THE RUSSET BURBANK,

01:36:16.630 --> 01:36:20.160
AND I'D BE SHOT FOR
SUGGESTING OTHERWISE.

01:36:20.160 --> 01:36:23.930
McDormand: DESPITE THE
DEMAND FOR RUSSET BURBANKS,

01:36:23.930 --> 01:36:27.860
THE BUSINESS OF GROWING THEM
IS FAR FROM A SURE THING.

01:36:27.860 --> 01:36:30.700
EACH YEAR, CRANNEY
AND HIS FAMILY

01:36:30.700 --> 01:36:33.560
HAVE TO SHELL OUT
MILLIONS OF DOLLARS

01:36:33.560 --> 01:36:37.760
FOR WATER, SEED, FERTILIZER,
CHEMICALS, AND LABOR.

01:36:37.760 --> 01:36:40.160
BUT THEY HAVE LITTLE
CONTROL OVER THE PRICE

01:36:40.160 --> 01:36:43.160
THEIR POTATOES WILL SELL
FOR AT HARVEST TIME.

01:36:43.160 --> 01:36:47.830
Cranney: IT'S VERY
RISKY, GROWING CROPS.

01:36:47.830 --> 01:36:52.360
WE HAD SOME REALLY HUGE LOSSES
ECONOMICALLY HERE ON THE FARM.

01:36:52.360 --> 01:36:56.930
I DON'T EVEN LIKE TO THINK
ABOUT IT, HOW BAD IT WAS.

01:36:56.930 --> 01:36:59.400
A LOT OF THE PEOPLE
IN THE COMMUNITY,

01:36:59.400 --> 01:37:00.830
FARMERS THAT WE GREW UP WITH,

01:37:00.830 --> 01:37:03.500
THAT HAVE BEEN HERE
AS LONG AS WE HAVE,

01:37:03.500 --> 01:37:06.060
NO LONGER HAVE THEIR OPERATIONS.

01:37:06.060 --> 01:37:09.130
MANY OF US, THE ONLY
WAY WE COULD SURVIVE WAS

01:37:09.130 --> 01:37:12.530
TO RE-MORTGAGE OUR FARMS
AND RE-MORTGAGE OUR LAND,

01:37:12.530 --> 01:37:14.460
AND THAT'S HOW WE
STAYED IN BUSINESS.

01:37:14.460 --> 01:37:16.460
YOU CAN ONLY DO --
DIP INTO THE WELL

01:37:16.460 --> 01:37:18.360
FOR SO LONG UNTIL
THE WELL GOES DRY.

01:37:18.360 --> 01:37:30.260
AND MANY OF US HAVE
BEEN TO THAT POINT.

01:37:30.260 --> 01:37:31.430
WELL, IT'S NOT TOO BAD HERE,

01:37:31.430 --> 01:37:33.530
BECAUSE YOU'RE
RUNNING ENOUGH VOLUME.

01:37:33.530 --> 01:37:35.030
THEY'RE FLOWING
PRETTY GOOD, BUT...

01:37:35.030 --> 01:37:37.530
McDormand: IN ADDITION TO THE
ECONOMIC PERILS HE FACES,

01:37:37.530 --> 01:37:40.960
CRANNEY MUST CONTEND WITH
BIOLOGICAL ADVERSARIES --

01:37:40.960 --> 01:37:45.460
THE INSECTS, FUNGI, AND VIRUSES
THAT PREY ON HIS PLANTS.

01:37:45.460 --> 01:37:49.600
AND HIS RUSSET BURBANKS
ARE ESPECIALLY VULNERABLE,

01:37:49.600 --> 01:37:51.730
BECAUSE THEY ARE GROWN
IN A MONOCULTURE,

01:37:51.730 --> 01:37:54.630
JUST LIKE THE LUMPER POTATOES
WERE, BACK IN IRELAND.

01:37:54.630 --> 01:37:59.760
IF AN ENEMY CAN KILL ONE OF
CRANNEY'S RUSSET BURBANKS,

01:37:59.760 --> 01:38:00.900
IT CAN KILL THEM ALL.

01:38:00.900 --> 01:38:04.430
MY ROLE AS A FARMER
IS TO HELP THE PLANT

01:38:04.430 --> 01:38:06.100
OUT-COMPETE THE
DIFFERENT PESTS,

01:38:06.100 --> 01:38:09.730
WHETHER THAT BE WEEDS OR
WHETHER THAT BE INSECTS

01:38:09.730 --> 01:38:13.700
OR A FUNGUS OF SOME SORT.

01:38:13.700 --> 01:38:17.800
IT'S A CONSTANT BATTLE THAT
WE HAVE TO FIGHT THOSE OFF

01:38:17.800 --> 01:38:20.130
AND TO PROTECT AGAINST THOSE.

01:38:20.130 --> 01:38:23.130
IT'S A RACE TO THE FINISH
LINE, WHETHER THE PESTS WIN

01:38:23.130 --> 01:38:24.700
OR WHETHER THE
POTATO PLANT WINS.

01:38:24.700 --> 01:38:28.430
McDormand: TO HELP HIS
POTATOES WIN THAT RACE,

01:38:28.430 --> 01:38:30.460
CRANNEY, LIKE THE
GREAT MAJORITY

01:38:30.460 --> 01:38:34.930
OF LARGE-SCALE POTATO GROWERS
IN THE UNITED STATES,

01:38:34.930 --> 01:38:36.830
USES CHEMICAL PESTICIDES.

01:38:36.830 --> 01:38:40.500
THE CHEMICALS THE
CRANNEYS USE CAN BE TOXIC,

01:38:40.500 --> 01:38:42.360
BUT THEY FOLLOW EPA GUIDELINES

01:38:42.360 --> 01:38:46.100
THAT ESTABLISH LEVELS
THAT ARE CONSIDERED

01:38:46.100 --> 01:38:47.330
SAFE TO USE.

01:38:47.330 --> 01:38:49.330
Cranney: I DON'T
NECESSARILY LIKE TO APPLY

01:38:49.330 --> 01:38:53.500
THE INSECTICIDES -- OR ANY
CHEMICAL OF ANY SORT --

01:38:53.500 --> 01:38:55.630
BUT IT'S SOMETHING
THAT NEEDS TO BE DONE

01:38:55.630 --> 01:39:00.460
IN ORDER TO KEEP
THE PLANTS HEALTHY.

01:39:00.460 --> 01:39:03.130
Man: WE DON'T USE A
CHEMICAL UNLESS WE NEED TO,

